Rarefaction Algorithm ------------------------------------------¶

  • Pick up a sampled site

  • Randomly select n subsamplings with or without replacement each with size of the least number of species or interactions from all the sampled sites

  • Compare curves along subsamplings of equal size

%DATA ---------------------
fid = fopen('./src/data/Pampa/Pampa_2020.csv');
in = fscanf(fid,'%c');
fclose(fid);
linesR = regexp(in,'(^,|)([^\n]+)', 'match');
All = char(linesR);
Forest = cell(length(All),1);
wR = unique_no_sort(linesR);
R = char(wR);

#categorize forest type
for k = 1:length(All);
    wHF = regexp(All(k,:),',');
    Forest(k,1) = All(k,1:wHF(1,1)-1);
end
wF = unique_no_sort(Forest);

for n = 2:length(wF); 
TypeOutput = zeros(length(R),4);
Type = zeros(1,1);
ForestType = zeros(1,2);
InsectType = zeros(1,1);
xR = zeros(1,1);
wHR1 = zeros(1,1);

wF(1,n)   
    cR = cellstr(wF(1,n));
    xR = regexpcell(linesR,cR);
    ForestType = cell(length(xR),1:2);
    %InsectType = cell(length(xR),1);
    
    for j = 1:length(xR);
        wHR1 = regexp(All(xR(1,j),:),',');
        ForestType(j,1) = All(xR(1,j),wHR1(1,2)+1:wHR1(1,3)-1);%Plant species
        ForestType(j,2) = All(xR(1,j),wHR1(1,4)+1:wHR1(1,5)-1);%Insect species
    end

    %RarefactionI 
    N = zeros(1,1);
    Type = unique(ForestType);
    N = length(ForestType);
    UNI = length(Type);
    
    %All --- 
    A = ForestType;
    [B,I,J] = unique(ForestType);
    
    for u = 1:length(A);
        New(u,1) = J(u,1);
        New(u,2) = J(u+length(A),1);
    end
    Total = unique(New,"rows");
    red=unifrnd(0,1); green=unifrnd(0,1); blue=unifrnd(0,1);
    
    R=10;
    for rep = 1:R; 
        U = zeros(1,2);
        for r = 1:N;
            S = unidrnd(length(New),r,1);
            Sampled = New(S,1:2);
            L = unique(Sampled,"rows");
            U(r,1) = r;
            U(r,2) = length(L);  
        end
        hold on
        plot(U(:,1),U(:,2),'k','color',[red green blue],'Markersize',36)
    end%rep  
    #pause   
end
set(gca,'FontSize',20)
xlabel('Number of flower visitors','fontsize',30)
ylabel('Number of unique interactions','fontsize',30)

Exercise: Do larger Sierras contain more species and interactions than the smaller ones?¶

## R --------------------
## Rarefaction
## --------------------
# For each site (sierra in Pampa_2020.csv) create a line plot with three lines (one for plants (Plant.AF8.species) 
# one for insects (Insect.AF8.species), and unique interactions (Insect.AF8.abundance)). 
# The x-axis is time (Day), and the y-axis is count. 
# These numbers should be normalized by the site that has the smallest number of samplings. 
# One way to do that is only take n random samples from each site, where n is the minimum number of available 
# samples among all sites. 
# columns 1,2,3,5,6 of the Pampa_2020.csv dataset are needed for this task

# Second plot is site area on the x axis (from area_sp.csv) and the y axis is the number of plants,
# insects, and interactions - with and without rarefaction.
# Third plot: Cumulative plot of number of unique interactions per area.

# install.packages('plyr')
library('plyr')
library('ggplot2')

## 1.1 Normalization
## ------------------
# data loading and preparation
df <- read.csv('src/data/Pampa/Pampa_2020.csv')
# exclude empty columns
df = df[, 1:7]
# Convert Day to Date format
df$Day <- as.Date(df$Day,  tryFormats = c("%d-%m-%Y", "%d/%m/%Y"))

sites = unique(df$Sierra)
min_samples = min(count(df, vars="Sierra")$freq)

# A new table where each all sites have exactly `min_samples` samples.
final_rows = vector()
for (site in sites){ 
  final_rows = c(final_rows, sample(which(df$Sierra == site), min_samples, replace=FALSE))
}
df2 = df[final_rows, ]

## 1.2 Plot 1
## -----------
In [2]:
### R --- 
for (site in sites){

  # get flowers per day
  rowsf = which(df2$Sierra == site)
  flowers = count(df2[rowsf,c("Plant.AF8.species", "Day")], vars=c("Day"))
  flowers$Quantity = "Flowers"

  # get insects per day
  rowsi = which((df2$Sierra == site) & (df2$Insect.AF8.species != "No visit"))
  insects = count(df2[rowsi,c("Insect.AF8.species", "Day")], vars=c("Day"))
  insects$Quantity = "Insects"

  # get interactions per day
  rowsi = which(df2$Sierra == site)
  interX = count(df2[rowsi,c("Insect.AF8.abundance", "Day")], vars=c("Day", "Insect.AF8.abundance"))
  interactions = insects
  for (day in unique(interX$Day)){
    rows = interX$Day == day
    c = sum(interX[rows, "Insect.AF8.abundance"] * interX[rows, "freq"]) 
    interactions[interactions$Day == day, "freq"] = c
  }
  interactions$Quantity = "Interactions"
 
    # plot
  sitedf = merge(merge(flowers, insects, all=TRUE), interactions, all=TRUE)
  p = ggplot(data=sitedf,
    aes(x=Day, y=freq, color=factor(Quantity))) + geom_line(size=1.2)  

    ##ggsave(paste(sit,filename = file.path("R","_abundance.png",sep=""), plot=p))
  ggsave(paste(site,filename = "_abundance.png", sep=""), plot=p)

}

        U1(r,1) = r;U1(r,2) = length(UN1);

        U2(r,1) = r;U2(r,2) = length(UN2); 
        
        w = intersect(UN1,UN2);#shared unique
        W12(r,1) = length(w);
        W12(r,2) = dis(n,m);#Distance ij 
    end
    
      # 4. Intersections interlayer
    count = count + 1;q = zeros(1,1);
    In(count,1) = dis(n,m); 
    intersection=find(U1(:,2)==U2(:,2));
    q = find(intersection) >= 10;
    In(count,2) = nnz(q);
    
    #. 5. PLOT
    hold on
    subplot(2,2,1)
    plot(U1(:,1),U1(:,2),'k','color',[red1 green1 blue1],'Markersize',36)
    hold on
    plot(U2(:,1),U2(:,2),'k','color',[red2 green2 blue2],'Markersize',36)
    set(gca,'FontSize',12)
    xlabel('Number of flower visitors','fontsize',12)
    ylabel('Number of unique interactions','fontsize',12)
    
    hold on
    subplot(2,2,2)
    plot(U2(:,1),W12(:,1),'k','color',[red3 green3 blue3],'Markersize',36)
    set(gca,'FontSize',12)
    xlabel('Number of flower visitors','fontsize',12)
    ylabel('Number of shared interactions','fontsize',12)
    
    hold on   
    subplot(2,2,3)
    plot(W12(:,2),W12(:,1),'ko','color',[red3 green3 blue3],'Markersize',14)
    set(gca,'FontSize',12)
    xlabel('Pairwise distance','fontsize',12)
    ylabel('Number of shared interactions','fontsize',12)   
    
    hold on
    subplot(2,2,4)
    plot(In(:,1),In(:,2),'ko','color',[red3 green3 blue3],'Markersize',14)
    set(gca,'FontSize',12)
    xlabel('Pairwise distance','fontsize',12)
    ylabel('Number of interlayer intersections','fontsize',12) 
 
    #hold off
   end#m Sites       
end#n Sites

Centrality: How do we account for spatial and interaction network position?¶

Multilayer betweenness centrality¶

Given : $\overrightarrow{B}(B_{ij})$, where $i$ is species $i$ and $j$ is the number of sites with species $i$ having at least one interacting partner

$$ \overrightarrow{B}(B_{ij}) = \Bigg[ {\small normal_{S}} \Bigg( \Large\sum_{s \neq j \neq t}\frac{\sigma_{st(j)}}{\sigma_{st}} \Bigg) \times {\small normal_{M}} \Bigg(\Large\sum_{s' \neq i \neq t'}\frac{\sigma_{s't'(i)}}{\sigma_{s't'}} \Bigg) \Bigg]$$

where $\sigma_{st}$ is total number or shortest paths from node $s$ to node $t$ and $\sigma_{st(j)}$ is the number of those paths that pass through $j$ (or $i$). Normalizing the metrics we obtain

$normal_{S}$ = $\frac{S(j) - \min(\overrightarrow{S})}{\max(\overrightarrow{S}) - \min(\overrightarrow{S})}$ for the spatial network and

$normal_{M}$ = $\frac{M(i) - \min(\overrightarrow{M})}{\max(\overrightarrow{M}) - \min(\overrightarrow{M})}$ for the interaction network,

which results in:

  • max(normal) = 1
  • min(normal) = 0

#WARNING! This function is called by PlantBetweennessRandom.m 

#This function returns the betweenness of all nodes in an adjacency (transformed from a bipartite) 
# Accounts for site centrality
# Betweenness centrality measure: number of shortest paths running through a vertex.

#INPUTS: Random ADJ data - plant-pollinator network
#INPUTS: Adjacency matrix (nxn)

#OUTPUTS: betweeness vector for each node (1xn)

#Routines used: numNodes.m, adj2adjL.m, simpleDijkstra.m, findAllShortestPaths.m
#-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Betweenness_centrality
# Example with a bipartite graph 

graphics_toolkit();
available_graphics_toolkits();
loaded_graphics_toolkits();
graphics_toolkit("gnuplot")

addpath(genpath(pwd))
pkg load statistics

#matrix adj comes from mbetweenrandom.m
n = numNodes(adj);
w = size(adj);
%coord
xy = zeros(w(1,1),2);
for z = 1:length(xy);
    xy(z,1) = unidrnd(100);
    xy(z,2) = unidrnd(100);
end
#plot
#clf;
#gplot (adj, xy, "o-");
#set (get (gca, ("children")), "markersize", 12);
#title ("gplot() of bit2uni Adjacency matrix");

spaths=inf(n,n);
betw = zeros(1,n);  
adjL = adj2adjL(adj);

for i = 1:n;
    uB = simpleDijkstra(adj,i);
    for l=1:n;
        if i==l; continue; end

        [allPaths, ~] = findAllShortestPaths(adjL,i,l, uB(l), allPaths={},path=[]);
        spaths(i,l) = length(allPaths);
        
        % for all paths in allPaths, parse out the path:
        for p=1:length(allPaths)
            path = strsplit(allPaths{p},'-');
            pathvec = [];
            for x=2:length(path)  % skip the first one
                pathvec = [pathvec str2num(path{x})];
            end
            betw(pathvec(2:length(pathvec)-1)) = betw(pathvec(2:length(pathvec)-1)) + 1/spaths(i,l);
        end
    end  % end of j=1:n
end      % end of i=1:n

#mbetweenrandom.m : Multilayer rarefaction random
#Betweenness centrality from spatial and interaction networks
#DEPENDENCIES
#PlantBetweennessRandom.m

# Melian@CH, Multilayer networks OCT NOV 2021

graphics_toolkit();
available_graphics_toolkits();
loaded_graphics_toolkits();
graphics_toolkit("gnuplot")

addpath(genpath(pwd))
pkg load statistics

# Make a random spatial matrix
s1 = 10;s2 = 10;adjS = rand(s1,s2)>.75;

# Compute betwenneess each site
S = numNodes(adjS);spaths=inf(s1,s2);
betwS = zeros(1,s1);adjL = adj2adjL(adjS);

for i=1:s1;
    uB = simpleDijkstra(adjS,i);
    for j=1:s2;
        if i==j; continue; end
        [allPaths, ~] = findAllShortestPaths(adjL,i,j, uB(j), allPaths={},path=[]);
        spaths(i,j) = length(allPaths);
        # for all paths in allPaths, parse out the path:
        for pat=1:length(allPaths)
            path = strsplit(allPaths{pat},'-');
            pathvec = [];
            for x=2:length(path) # skip the first one
                pathvec = [pathvec str2num(path{x})];
            end
            betwS(pathvec(2:length(pathvec)-1)) = betwS(pathvec(2:length(pathvec)-1)) + 1/spaths(i,j);
        end
    end  # end of j=1:s1
end      # end of i=1:s2

#Presence/Absence plant matrix
pl = 10;PA = rand(pl,s1)>.75
BC = zeros(pl,s1);

for ii = 1:pl;#loop plant i
ii
    red=unifrnd(0,1); green=unifrnd(0,1); blue=unifrnd(0,1);#def color each species i
    for jj = 1:s1;
        if PA(ii,jj) == 1;        
           a = unidrnd(15);A = rand(pl,a)>.75;# Make a random MxN adjacency bipartite matrix
           adj = [zeros(pl,pl), A;A', zeros(a,a)];# Expand out to symmetric (M+N)x(M+N) matrix
           PlantBetweennessRandom;
           Bc(ii,jj) =  betwS(1,jj) * betw(1,ii);
        else
           PA(ii,jj) = 0;
        end
    end#site
Bci = sort(Bc(ii,:),2,'descend');#Rank output
rank = 1:length(Bci);
hold on
plot(rank,Bci,'k','color',[red green blue],'Markersize',12)
set(gca,'FontSize',12)
xlabel('Rank species centrality','fontsize',12)
ylabel('Betweenness','fontsize',12) 
end

# --------------------------
## 2. Betweenness centrality
# --------------------------

# 2.1 Create a network of sites where a node is a site and a link is present when distance (from DistanceMatrixPampa.csv dataset) between two sites is less than a threshold. Then calculate a betweenness centrality score for each node.
# 2.2 go through the list of each plant and insect, and sum the centrality scores of all the sites in which the species is present. Create a bar plot from these centrality scores for all plants and insects.
# Plant/insect centrality: For each site, you have a plant/insect network. Get a centrality score for each plant for each site.
# multiply the centrality of each species within sites to the centrality of the sites in which it appears. That will be the centrality score of the species.
# Plot the distribution of the centralities of a species.

## 2.1 Site network
library(igraph)
library(comprehenr)
connectedness_threshold = 10

ddf = read.csv('src/data/Pampa/DistanceMatrixPampa.csv')
site_names = c("Sierra", "Difuntos", "Valdez", "La Brava", "Volcan", "Vigilancia", "Volcancito", "Paulino", "Bachicha", "Difuntito", "Cinco cerros", "Barrosa", "La Paja", "Piedra Alta", "Los Pinos", "Amarante", "La Chata", "El Morro", "La Larga")
ddf[,1] = site_names[2:ncol(ddf)]
colnames(ddf) = site_names

# Choose only sites for which there are plant/insect sampling
sampled_sites = unique(df2$Sierra)
valid_sites = to_vec(for (i in 1:ncol(ddf)) if (site_names[i] %in% sampled_sites) i)  # needs comprehenr

# create a distance matrix
distmat = as.matrix(ddf[valid_sites-1,valid_sites])
dim(distmat)

# Create an adjacency matrix
adjmat = matrix(0, nrow(distmat), ncol(distmat))
connections = distmat <= connectedness_threshold
adjmat[connections] = 1

# create the graph
site_graph = graph_from_adjacency_matrix(distmat, mode="undirected")

# graph's betweenness centrality
site_btwn = betweenness(site_graph)

## 2.2 Within network betweenness centralities
plants = unique(df2$Plant.AF8.species)
insects = unique(df2$Insect.AF8.species)
all_species = c(plants,insects)
all_betweenness = matrix(0.0, length(plants) + length(insects), length(valid_sites))
for (ind in 1:length(valid_sites)){
  site = site_names[valid_sites[ind]]

  rowss = which((df2$Sierra == site)  & (df2$Insect.AF8.species != "No visit"))
  interactions = count(df2[rowss,c("Plant.AF8.species", "Insect.AF8.species", "Insect.AF8.abundance")], vars=c("Plant.AF8.species", "Insect.AF8.species"))

  # create a graph
  adjlist = interactions[, 1:2]

  site_plants = unique(adjlist[,1])
  site_insects = unique(adjlist[,2])
  alls = c(site_plants, site_insects)
  nallspecies = length(alls)
  alladjmat = matrix(0, nallspecies, nallspecies)

  for (row in 1:nrow(adjlist)){
    pind = which(alls == adjlist[row, 1])[1]
    iind = which(alls == adjlist[row, 2])[1]
    alladjmat[pind, iind] = 1
  }

  inx_graph = graph_from_adjacency_matrix(alladjmat, mode="undirected")
  btwn = betweenness(inx_graph)

  for (i in 1:length(alls)){
    ff = which(all_species == alls[i])[1]
    all_betweenness[ff, ind] = btwn[i]
  }
}

# plot
sorted_per_row = matrix(0.0, length(plants) + length(insects), length(valid_sites))
for (row in 1:nrow(all_betweenness)){
  sorted_per_row[row,] = sort(all_betweenness[row, ], decreasing=TRUE)
}

#pdf("plots/species_betweenness_centrality.pdf")
matplot(t(sorted_per_row), type="l", ylab="Betweenness centrality", xlab="Rank species centerality")

# normalize the betweenness values so that they are between 0 and 1

normalized_betweenness = matrix(0.0, length(plants) + length(insects), length(valid_sites))
sum_betweenness = colSums(all_betweenness)
for (row in 1:nrow(all_betweenness)){
  normalized_betweenness[row,] = all_betweenness[row, ] / sum_betweenness
}

# plot
sorted_per_row_normalized = matrix(0.0, length(plants) + length(insects), length(valid_sites))
for (row in 1:nrow(normalized_betweenness)){
  sorted_per_row_normalized[row,] = sort(normalized_betweenness[row, ], decreasing=TRUE)
}

#pdf("plots/species_betweenness_centrality_normalized.pdf")

Take home message¶

  • Simplest rarefaction accounting for sampling size ##### Do larger islands contain higher number of interactions and species than the smaller ones?

  • Numbers of interaction crossings among sites ##### Do the number of crossings decay with distance among sites?

  • Rank centrality distribution in multilayer networks ##### How does rank centrality distribution decay in multilayer network?
